      "id": "review::.::holistic::error_consistency::mixed_error_strategies_in_utils",
      "kind": "issue",
      "confidence": "high",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "summary": "utils.py uses two different error strategies for I/O failures: get_file_hash raises OSError while clean_and_parse_json returns an error dict",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "error_consistency",
        "related_files": [
          "CLI/multivol/api_server/utils.py"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "get_file_hash(): docstring says 'Raises OSError if the file cannot be read'; calculate_sha256() propagates FileNotFoundError from open()",
          "clean_and_parse_json(): returns {\"error\": \"File not found\", \"raw_output\": \"\"} when file is missing instead of raising",
          "Callers of both functions must use completely different error-handling patterns even though both are reading files"
        ],
        "suggestion": "Decide on one strategy for the module. Since callers are Flask routes, returning error dicts is more idiomatic for utils used at the HTTP layer. Either (a) have get_file_hash return None on failure and document it, or (b) have clean_and_parse_json raise FileNotFoundError on missing file. Apply the chosen strategy consistently.",
        "reasoning": "",
        "content_hash": "b2ec8365"
      },
